sis scenarios gave rise to improvisation and the – sometimes quite dramatic – breaking of practice boundaries. The originality of the text lies not only in the breadth of wartime practices considered, but also the international scope of both the contributors and the nurses they consider. It will therefore appeal to academics and students in the history of nursing and war, nursing work and the history of medicine and war from across the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary nursingxHistoryx19th century. 0aMilitary nursingxHistoryx20th century. 0aMilitary nursingxHistoryy19th century. 0aMilitary nursingxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aAmerican Civil War.  aArmy Nursing Reserve.  aBergen-Belsen.  aCrimean War.  aFirst World War.  aFlorence Nightingale.  aKorean War.  aNORMASH.  aRAAF.  aSecond Anglo-Boer War.  aSecond World War.  aSpanish Civil War.  acivilian nurses.  aflight nurses.  amilitary nurses.  atrained theatre nurses.  atyphoid epidemics.  avolunteer nurses.  awartime nursing.1 aBrooks, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDahl, Maxine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFause, Ashild, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallett, Christine E, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallett, Christine E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallett, Christine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarris, Kirsty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmst